# Register guidance

Applied AI Rig registers are portable, reviewable indexes for decision-relevant engineering records. They
are not intended to replace databases, observability platforms, experiment trackers, data catalogs,
incident systems, billing systems, or runtime audit stores.

> One row per decision-relevant record, not one row per runtime event.

## Choose the system of record

Choose and record one operating mode for each register.

### Embedded register

The versioned CSV is the system of record. Use this mode when the register is small, changes infrequently,
has one owner or a coordinated group of writers, contains no sensitive payload, and benefits from pull
request review. This is often appropriate for model, data, service, action, and misuse-case inventories in
small or medium projects.

### External index

An access-controlled external tool is the system of record. The CSV keeps only the subset needed to explain
decisions, releases, claims, risks, or incidents, together with a stable external reference. Use this mode
for high-volume activity, concurrent writers, sensitive metadata, advanced queries, retention enforcement,
or organization-wide workflows.

Document the chosen system, accountable owner, access path, and reconciliation cadence in the module
README or a linked project decision. Do not maintain two competing systems of record.

## Row contract

Every row must have one declared grain: the exact real-world record represented by one row. IDs must be
stable and unique within their register. References such as `decision_id`, `evidence_id`, `run_id`, and
external references must resolve to the canonical record or clearly remain unknown.

Before adding rows, define:

- which columns are required, optional, controlled, or allowed to be `unknown`;
- the owner responsible for correctness and review;
- when a row is created, updated, closed, superseded, archived, or reconciled;
- the permitted values for status-like fields;
- the source and timestamp for measured, estimated, or billed values;
- whether the CSV or an external tool is authoritative.

Do not silently delete invalid, failed, declined, or superseded records when they remain relevant to an
engineering decision. Mark their state and link the evidence or decision that explains it.

## Progressive completion

The full CSV header is the stable schema, not a demand to complete every column immediately. Start with the
minimum useful first entry below, then complete additional fields when a decision, claim, risk, review, or
operating responsibility needs them. Use `unknown` when the absence itself matters. Leave a field empty only
when it is truly not applicable or the module guidance defines an empty value.

| Register | Minimum useful first entry |
|---|---|
| `model_register.csv` | `model_id`, `owner`, `provider`, `model`, `purpose`, `decision_id` |
| `api_usage.csv` | `timestamp_utc`, `run_id`, `provider`, `model`, `measurement`, usage or cost fields, `evidence_id` |
| `data_register.csv` | `data_id`, `owner`, `provenance`, `purpose`, `classification`, `allowed_destinations`, `decision_id` |
| `experiments.csv` | `timestamp_utc`, `run_id`, `decision_id`, `model`, `hypothesis`, `primary_metric`, `primary_value`, `result` |
| `action_register.csv` | `action_id`, `tool`, `side_effect`, `resource_scope`, `permission`, `human_approval`, `decision_id` |
| `misuse_cases.csv` | `case_id`, `asset_or_goal`, `scenario`, `expected_prevention`, `response`, `residual_risk` |
| `service_register.csv` | `service_id`, `owner`, `users_or_consumers`, `health_signals`, `operating_limits`, `degraded_mode`, `rollback_reference` |
| `incident_register.csv` | `incident_id`, `opened_at`, `status`, `owner`, `impact`, `mitigation`, `rollback` |

Progressive completion reduces ceremony; it does not turn an unknown into evidence. Before a row supports a
published claim, release, access decision, or incident closure, complete every field needed to review that
specific use and link the canonical sources.

## Scale and externalization triggers

Move the system of record out of Git when any of these conditions becomes material:

- rows are produced automatically for runtime events;
- frequent or concurrent writers cause merge conflicts;
- the file becomes difficult to review as a complete change;
- users need filtering, aggregation, joins, dashboards, retention jobs, or access control;
- row-level permissions or sensitive metadata cannot be represented safely in the repository;
- another organizational tool already owns the lifecycle and audit history;
- updates must be transactional or immediately consistent.

Externalization is not a failure of the Rig. The CSV then becomes a deliberate decision index or may contain
only a documented pointer to the canonical system.

## Register-specific grain

| Register | Intended row | Do not use it for |
|---|---|---|
| `model_register.csv` | One governed model configuration or version policy | Every inference request |
| `api_usage.csv` | One decision-relevant aggregate for a run, release, workload, or billing period | One row per API call or trace span |
| `data_register.csv` | One governed data source, dataset, or materially distinct derivative | Individual records or personal data |
| `experiments.csv` | One baseline, decision-relevant variant, regression check, or cited final run | Every exploratory trace or repeated sample |
| `action_register.csv` | One category of model-directed action and its control boundary | Every action execution or audit event |
| `misuse_cases.csv` | One representative abuse or failure scenario | Raw security telemetry |
| `service_register.csv` | One operated workload or service | Individual health samples or alerts |
| `incident_register.csv` | One incident summary linked to its canonical timeline and review | Full event timelines, logs, or chat transcripts |

For `api_usage.csv`, aggregate request counts, tokens, latency, failures, retries, and cost at a grain that
supports a decision or reconciliation. Preserve detailed usage in billing or observability systems. For
`experiments.csv`, retain runs that establish baselines, affect choices, support claims, or demonstrate
regressions; keep detailed prompts, responses, samples, spans, and secondary metrics in the experiment
system.

## Collaboration and Git

CSV works best with a single accountable owner, append-oriented changes, stable ordering, UTF-8, and one
logical record per line. Avoid spreadsheet features, formulas, embedded newlines, and manual column
reordering. Quote fields according to standard CSV rules and review the rendered diff before merging.

If concurrent writers are common, use an external system of record and periodically reconcile the
decision-relevant index. Do not solve repeated merge conflicts by silently accepting both versions; check
for duplicate IDs, conflicting states, and lost updates.

## Sensitive and prohibited content

Never put secrets, credential values, private endpoints, prompts, model responses, personal records,
sensitive payloads, provider request IDs, raw traces, or unrestricted incident evidence in versioned
registers. Store access-controlled material in its canonical system and keep only a safe reference and
decision-relevant summary.

Repository visibility does not make sensitive content safe, and later deletion from Git does not guarantee
removal from history or clones.

## Review checklist

Before relying on a register:

- confirm its row grain and system of record;
- confirm IDs and references are stable and resolvable;
- confirm unknown values remain explicit rather than guessed;
- confirm the repository contains no prohibited content;
- confirm aggregate measurements state their period and basis;
- confirm external references are durable and access-controlled;
- confirm the owner and reconciliation cadence are current;
- externalize the register when volume, concurrency, querying, retention, or access needs exceed Git.
